     bool ShenandoahAlwaysClearSoftRefs            = true                                 {experimental} {ergonomic}     Unconditionally clear soft references, instead of using any other cleanup policy. This minimizes footprint at expense ofmore soft reference churn in applications.
    ccstr ShenandoahGCHeuristics                   = compact                                   {product} {command line}  GC heuristics to use. This fine-tunes the GC mode selected, by choosing when to start the GC, how much to process on each cycle, and what other features to automatically enable. When -XX:ShenandoahGCMode is generational, the only supported option is the default, adaptive. Possible values are: adaptive - adapt to maintain the given amount of free heap at all times, even during the GC cycle; static - trigger GC when free heap falls below a specified threshold; aggressive - run GC continuously, try to evacuate everything; compact - run GC more frequently and with deeper targets to free up more memory.
    uintx ShenandoahGarbageThreshold               = 10                                   {experimental} {ergonomic}     How much garbage a region has to contain before it would be taken for collection. This a guideline only, as GC heuristics may select the region for collection even if it has little garbage. This also affects how much internal fragmentation the collector accepts. In percents of heap region size.
    uintx ShenandoahGuaranteedGCInterval           = 30000                                {experimental} {ergonomic}     Many heuristics would guarantee a concurrent GC cycle at least with this interval. This is useful when large idle intervals are present, where GC can run without stealing time from active application. Time is in milliseconds. Setting this to 0 disables the feature.
    uintx ShenandoahImmediateThreshold             = 100                                  {experimental} {ergonomic}     The cycle may shortcut when enough garbage can be reclaimed from the immediate garbage (completely garbage regions). In percents of total garbage found. Setting this threshold to 100 effectively disables the shortcut.
     bool ShenandoahImplicitGCInvokesConcurrent    = true                                 {experimental} {ergonomic}     Should internally-caused GC requests invoke concurrent cycles, should they do the stop-the-world (Degenerated / Full GC)? Many heuristics automatically enable this. This option is similar to global ExplicitGCInvokesConcurrent.
     bool ShenandoahUncommit                       = true                                 {experimental} {ergonomic}     Allow to uncommit memory under unused regions and metadata. This optimizes footprint at expense of allocation latency in regions that require committing back. Uncommits would be disabled by some heuristics, or with static heap size.
    uintx ShenandoahUncommitDelay                  = 1000                                 {experimental} {ergonomic}     Uncommit memory for regions that were not used for more than this time. First use after that would incur allocation stalls. Actively used regions would never be uncommitted, because they do not become unused longer than this delay. Time is in milliseconds. Setting this delay to 0 effectively uncommits regions almost immediately after they become unused.
